@article{ISI:000297390900025,
 abstract = {Electrodeposition was used to deposit cobalt over polycarbonate membrane
(PCM), which was used as stable supported catalyst in hydrolysis of
sodium borohydride NaBH(4). We selected PCM as support owing to its
lightness, easy handling, stability, and porous structure with nanosized
channels. Our primary objective was to obtain a catalytic film resistant
to both physical degradation and delamination while H(2) bubbled on its
surface. A thin film consisting of mushroom-like cobalt
nanoarchitectures were prepared. By SEM, we observed that it is strongly
embedded into the PCM thickness, with the anchoring occurring through
the channels. This shaped catalyst was mechanically stable and did not
show degradation during the reaction. The main results are reported and
discussed in details herein. Copyright (C) 2011, Hydrogen Energy
Publications, LLC. Published by Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.},
